    <Paragraph FontSize="22">Methods for Animating Properties
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>With code, there are several other ways you can animate. The following list describes a few of the different approaches you can use.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc">
      <ListItem>
        <Paragraph>Apply animations directly.
        </Paragraph>

        <Paragraph>Use the BeginAnimation method of animatable objects to apply a single animation without creating a storyboard. For an example, see the Local Animations Sample.
        </Paragraph>

      </ListItem>

      <ListItem>
        <Paragraph>Create and manipulate your own clocks.
        </Paragraph>

        <Paragraph>Create your timelines and animations then use the CreateClock method to generate their corresponding clock objects. You can then apply the clocks you created to the property they animate by calling the ApplyAnimationClock method on each object to be animated. For examples, see the <Hyperlink NavigateUri="d0b520e0-2f18-4cef-977f-2909e709548a.xaml">How to: Interactively Control a Clock</Hyperlink>
 example.
        </Paragraph>

      </ListItem>

      <ListItem>
        <Paragraph>Animate frame-by-frame.
        </Paragraph>

        <Paragraph>Use the CompositionTarget class to receive notification when rendering occurs. You can then manipulate your objects each time they render. For an example, see the Per-Frame Animation Sample .
        </Paragraph>

      </ListItem>

    </List>

